```suggestion
    enum { outer(0), inner(1) } ClientECHType;
```

Just to make sure I'm reading this right: the intent of this text is that you'd leave all other extensions of ClientHelloOuter unchanged, independent of what was in HelloRetryRequest?

Not an objection. Just trying to understand what this is saying.

Though, as I write this, this does do something kinda interesting. Suppose your first ClientHello was:

```
ClientHelloOuter{
  alpn{h2},
  key_share{x25519{aaa}}
  supported_groups{x25519, secp256r1}
  server_name{"public.example"}
  encrypted_client_hello{
    EncodedClientHelloInner{
      outer_extensions{alpn, key_share, supported_groups}
      server_name{"example.com"}
      encrypted_client_hello{}
    }
    # Expands to:
    # ClientHelloInner{
    #  alpn{h2},
    #  key_share{x25519{aaa}}
    #  supported_groups{x25519, secp256r1}
    #  server_name{"example.com"}
    #  encrypted_client_hello{}
    # }
  }
}
```

Now you get a HelloRetryRequest:

```
HelloRetryRequest{
  key_share{secp256r1}
  encrypted_client_hello{...}
}
```

This is an ECH-accept HRR, so the new ClientHelloInner is:

```
ClientHelloInner{
  alpn{h2},
  key_share{secp256r1{bbb}}
  supported_groups{x25519, secp256r1}
  server_name{"example.com"}
  encrypted_client_hello{}
}
```

But if our rules say you don't change ClientHelloOuter, the key_share extension no longer matches. You can only compress alpn and supported_groups. But those extensions are no longer contiguous, and a sufficiently strict reading of RFC8446 4.1.2 probably forbids reordering the extensions.

Some ideas on ways out of this:

* Don't compress the second ClientHelloInner at all. But this means wasting bytes because we're obligated to resend a bunch of stuff now known to be useless.
* Allow the second ClientHelloOuter to arbitrarily change if the client feels like it. Then the client can arrange to compress the same way as it previously did (probably reusing the same code as above). But this means the rules on what the client does are weird and open-ended.
* Don't compress the second ClientHelloInner at all *and* drop all extensions from the ClientHelloOuter because it's totally irrelevant at this point. This avoids wasting bytes and is well-defined, but it means yet another ad-hoc ClientHello serializer, albeit a pretty straightforward one.
* Relax RFC8446 4.1.2 rules. You compress the ones that didn't change and reorder as needed. Wastes less bytes but still some bytes. Also it means the client's compression logic gets even more interesting cases.

@davidben two quick comments:

1. If we say "anything outside that syntax is invalid," without giving a function to determine if it's invalid, then we're back at Martin's criticism, right?
2. If the check is deferred to the application when validating the certificate, doesn't this run the risk of including an IP address in the outer SNI extension?

